Year to date, the reported value is 3,791,076 over nine months of data (421,231 average). Bin 3 covers the range of remaining monthly average values from 336,308 to 536,308. While the low end of that range is comfortably normal in the pre-pandemic data, there is no evidence that the numbers will drop back to those levels within the next three months. On the other end, there is only one occurrence of a reported value above the upper end of that range (July 2020). The data just doesn't support an outcome other than bin 3, barring some extremely rare disruption with far less than a 1% probability of occurrence.
3.791M so far; we need ~ 1M in the next 3 months in order to reach bin 3.

Holding for now, but rethinking my logic a bit. I previously thought there would most likely be more business applications in 2022 than 2021, but upon further reflection, a weaker economy might hurt those prospects, and I think there is a chance of a recession given that the Fed is trying to rein in inflation and reverse their Zero-Interest Rate Policy. Furthermore, supply chain issues, a potential Chinese economy crash, etc. all lead me to be less certain that the American economy will greatly expand in 2022. On the other hand, the winding down of the pandemic might stimulate our economy significantly, so overall, I'm just not certain enough one way or the other.

On pace for 5.48m applications in 2021, which is unchanged since my first forecast 6 weeks ago. For the last four months of available data in 2021, there were fewer applications than in the same four months of 2020 (Jun-Sep).

After a long plateau from at least 2005 to 2014, new business starts began growing from about 2.5m annually up to 3.5m in 2019. Applications soared further from June 2020 onward. There is a suggestion of tapering in recent months but it's not a clear trend. 2021 is on pace to shatter the 2020 record of 4.4m applications, with a current pace of 5.5m.

Pre-pandemic baseline is 3.5M and we should revert toward that level as the economic forces stabilize. Reversion may not be complete as dynamics have shifted, but should continue toward the mean through next year. My biggest uncertainty has to do with the growth of solopreneurs working as independent contractors under business licenses.
On second thought, the previous was a dumb forecast. Return to the mean.
